In July and August 2004, devastating floods in Bangladesh claimed over 700 lives and submerged 38% of the country, displacing millions.
The Brahmaputra River surged dangerously high, prompting evacuations and relief efforts.
Monsoon rains and snowmelt from the Himalayas worsened the situation, affecting India, Bangladesh, and Nepal.
The death toll rose as floods ravaged villages, leaving thousands stranded.
The government and military scrambled to provide aid, but the floodwaters continued to rise, threatening more regions.
